to the editor the case for the electoral college is compelling as your dec 19 editorial argues but electoral votes can be awarded without the use of the electors themselves they serve no useful purpose and offer an opportunity for mischief also it makes little sense to award all of a state 's electoral votes to a candidate when his margin of victory is less than the margin of error in such a case the electoral votes should be equally divided and since we will have eliminated the electors there will be no difficulty in awarding fractional votes for those states with an odd number of electoral votes sherman siegel king of prussia pa dec 19 2000

